      <div set:html={`<h2 id="how-to-convert-pdf-to-epub-on-mac-windows-and-online-2026">How to Convert PDF to EPUB on Mac, Windows, and Online (2026)</h2>
<p>PDF and EPUB serve fundamentally different purposes. PDFs preserve exact formatting — making them perfect for print-ready documents — while EPUB reflows text to fit any screen size, giving readers a comfortable experience on ereaders, phones, and tablets.</p>
<p>If you've been wondering <strong>how to convert PDF to EPUB</strong>, you're in the right place. This guide covers every method available in 2026: desktop software for Mac and Windows, and free online converters.</p>
<hr />
<h2 id="why-convert-pdf-to-epub">Why Convert PDF to EPUB?</h2>
<p>PDF files are "fixed layout" — they look the same on every device, but they don't adapt. On a small ereader screen, that means constant zooming, panning, and a poor reading experience.</p>
<p>EPUB is the opposite. It's a "reflowable" format, meaning:</p>
<ul>
<li>Text adjusts to fit any screen size automatically</li>
<li>Font size is adjustable by the reader</li>
<li>Bookmarking and highlights work properly</li>
<li>File sizes are typically smaller</li>
</ul>
<p>The result is a much more comfortable reading experience, especially on dedicated ereaders like Kindle, Kobo, or Kobo Clara.</p>
<hr />
<h2 id="method-1-online-converter-fastest-no-install">Method 1: Online Converter (Fastest — No Install)</h2>
<p>The quickest way to convert PDF to EPUB without installing anything is using a free online converter like <strong>converter-epub.com</strong>.</p>
<p>converter-epub.com handles the conversion entirely in your browser — your files never leave your device. Note that it currently supports DOCX, HTML, and TXT formats. For PDF files, you'll need a desktop application or a dedicated PDF-to-EPUB converter.</p>
<h3 id="step-by-step-convert-pdf-to-epub-online">Step-by-Step: Convert PDF to EPUB Online</h3>
<p><strong>Step 1: Choose a PDF-to-EPUB Converter</strong></p>
<p>Select a desktop or online tool that specifically supports PDF input. Look for tools that handle PDF text extraction well, as PDFs can contain either text layers or scanned images.</p>
<p><strong>Step 2: Upload Your PDF</strong></p>
<p>Drag and drop your PDF into the converter. For scanned PDFs (image-based), the tool will need OCR (optical character recognition) to extract the text.</p>
<p><strong>Step 3: Adjust Settings</strong></p>
<p>Most converters let you set:
- Book title and author
- Chapter detection
- Font preferences</p>
<p><strong>Step 4: Convert and Download</strong></p>
<p>Click convert and download your EPUB file. Test it on your ereader or app to make sure chapters and formatting transferred correctly.</p>
<hr />
<h2 id="method-2-calibre-free-mac-windows-linux">Method 2: Calibre (Free — Mac, Windows, Linux)</h2>
<p><a href="https://calibre-ebook.com/">Calibre</a> is the gold standard for ebook management and conversion. It's free, open-source, and handles even difficult PDFs better than most paid tools.</p>
<h3 id="step-by-step-pdf-to-epub-with-calibre">Step-by-Step: PDF to EPUB with Calibre</h3>
<p><strong>Step 1: Download and Install Calibre</strong></p>
<p>Download Calibre from <a href="https://calibre-ebook.com/">calibre-ebook.com</a>. The installer is available for macOS, Windows, and Linux.</p>
<p><strong>Step 2: Add Your PDF</strong></p>
<p>Click the "Add books" button (top left, looks like a green folder with a plus sign) and select your PDF file.</p>
<p><strong>Step 3: Select and Convert</strong></p>
<p>Right-click on your added book, then select <strong>"Convert books" → "Convert individually"</strong>.</p>
<p>In the output format dropdown at the top right of the conversion dialog, select <strong>EPUB</strong>.</p>
<p><strong>Step 4: Tweak Options (Optional)</strong></p>
<p>Navigate through the left panel options:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Metafloppy</strong> — Set your book title and author</li>
<li><strong>Page setup</strong> — Choose input and output page margins</li>
<li><strong>Heuristics</strong> — Enable "OCR the input" if you have a scanned PDF</li>
<li><strong>Table of Contents</strong> — Let Calibre attempt auto-detection of chapters</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Step 5: Convert</strong></p>
<p>Click <strong>OK</strong> at the bottom right. Calibre will process the PDF and add the EPUB to your library.</p>
<p><strong>Step 6: Transfer to Your Device</strong></p>
<p>Connect your ereader via USB and use Calibre's device icon to send the EPUB directly, or right-click the book and choose "Open containing folder" to find the file manually.</p>
<h3 id="calibre-pdf-to-epub-limitations">Calibre PDF-to-EPUB Limitations</h3>
<p>Calibre handles PDF text extraction well for text-based PDFs. Scanned PDFs require OCR, which Calibre can perform but results vary depending on scan quality. Complex PDF layouts (multi-column, tables, sidebars) often don't convert cleanly — in those cases, manual editing of the EPUB may be needed.</p>
<h3 id="calibre-ocr-setup-with-tesseract">OCR Setup with Tesseract</h3>
<p>Calibre ships with basic OCR, but for serious scanned PDFs you'll want Tesseract 5.3.x or later installed and routed through Calibre.</p>
<p><strong>Install Tesseract.</strong> On macOS: <code>brew install tesseract</code>. On Windows: grab the installer from the UB Mannheim build on GitHub. On Linux: <code>sudo apt install tesseract-ocr</code> on Debian/Ubuntu or <code>sudo dnf install tesseract</code> on Fedora.</p>
<p><strong>Language packs.</strong> Tesseract ships with English only. On macOS, <code>brew install tesseract-lang</code> adds 100+ languages at once. On Linux, install per language: <code>tesseract-ocr-deu</code> (German), <code>tesseract-ocr-fra</code> (French), <code>tesseract-ocr-spa</code> (Spanish). Calibre's "Tesseract language" dropdown in the OCR tab picks them up — restart Calibre after installing new ones.</p>
<p><strong>Quality settings.</strong> In Calibre 7.0+, the "PDF Input" section has a "Tesseract OCR options" field. For noisy scans, add <code>--oem 1 --psm 3</code> to switch to the LSTM neural net engine and assume a fully laid-out page. For plain prose, <code>--psm 6</code> (uniform text block) usually gives cleaner output. Error rates above 2% on a spot-check usually mean the scan was too low-res — re-scan at 300 DPI minimum for usable results.</p>
<hr />
<h2 id="method-3-adobe-acrobat-pro-paid">Method 3: Adobe Acrobat Pro (Paid)</h2>
<p>If you already have Adobe Acrobat Pro, it includes an EPUB conversion feature.</p>
<h3 id="step-by-step-pdf-to-epub-with-adobe-acrobat-pro">Step-by-Step: PDF to EPUB with Adobe Acrobat Pro</h3>
<p><strong>Step 1: Open your PDF in Acrobat Pro</strong></p>
<p><strong>Step 2: Go to Export</strong></p>
<p>Click <strong>File</strong> → <strong>Export To</strong> → <strong>EPUB</strong>.</p>
<p><strong>Step 3: Configure and Export</strong></p>
<p>Set your book metadata and click <strong>Export</strong>. Choose where to save the EPUB file.</p>
<h3 id="adobe-acrobat-limitations">Adobe Acrobat Limitations</h3>
<p>Adobe Acrobat's PDF-to-EPUB conversion is available only in the Pro version. It costs around $23/month as part of an Acrobat subscription. The conversion quality is good for text-heavy PDFs but can struggle with complex layouts. Multi-column text may not reflow properly in the resulting EPUB.</p>
